:: linkdemo {"position":"750,125","size":"100,100"}
Did you think you were going somewhere cool? Uhn... no. All the links on the previous page just come here. But you could have designed them to take you to different pages.

To construct a link you wrap the text you want to serve as the link in double square brackets. By default, the text in the square brackets will be the name of the page where the link will take your reader. However, you can conceal your page names: place a dash and an angle braket into the link command. 

So you might do something link -- 'impactful->Proceed'. In this case, your reader would see the word 'impactful', but the page would actually be called 'Proceed'.

Now that you understand how to construct links, let's work on making your pages and texts more [[impactful->Proceed]].


:: twinefiles1 {"position":"775,575","size":"100,100"}
Let's say you've completed your TWINE project! It is amazing! How do you share it with the world?

You have two options. 

In the TWINE software, you should see a menu bar at the top. You need to go to the 'Build' section. Once you click on the 'Build' tab you should see the option to 'Publish to File' and 'Export As Twee'.






